------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. UUID PERMANENCE
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Every item (note, notebook, file) receives a UUID at creation.
UUID is never changed. It survives:
- Rename operations
- Move operations between notebooks
- Deletion and resurrection
- Export and re-import
- Git commit history
- Platform migration
- Hard erase (UUID persists in commit history until purged)

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. NOTEBOOK REGISTRY & PORTABILITY
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Central registry maps notebook UUID → filesystem path.
Notebooks can live in any location: default, custom, external drives, network shares.
Custom paths persist in structure.json.
Cross-platform path normalization enables discovery and duplicate prevention.
Missing paths are detected and cleaned automatically.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. GIT AS ITEM-LEVEL TEMPORAL DATABASE
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Every state change is committed to Git.
Each commit message contains the UUID of the affected item.
Structured commit messages encode:
- Action (CREATED, UPDATED, RENAMED, DELETED, RESTORED)
- Content type (NOTE, FILE, NOTEBOOK, SUBNOTEBOOK)
- Title/name
- Context (notebook path, parent)
- Metadata (editor, line count, word count, file extension)
- Parent UUID (immediate container)
- Root UUID (top-level notebook)

Complete item history is queryable via:

    git log --grep uuid:<UUID> --all

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. THREE-FILE ATOMIC ARCHITECTURE
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Each notebook is a self-contained directory with three files:

structure.json
    Hierarchy, UUIDs, parent-child relationships, custom_path.
    No content. Purely structural.

notes.json
    UUID → content mapping for regular notes.
    Plain text. Human-readable. Git-diffable.

files.json
    UUID → content mapping for file notes (80+ extensions).
    Preserves syntax highlighting context via extension mapping.
    Enables extension-based search: s .py, s .md, s .js

Write operations are atomic: write .tmp → fsync → rename.
Crash recovery is inherent; temporary files are ignored on restart.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5. RELATIVE ANCESTOR NAVIGATION (FISH-EYE)
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Current location stored as stack: {'screen': str, 'id': str, 'page': int}.

Full hierarchy is truncated to terminal width via fish-eye algorithm:
    ...[1]LEVEL8/[2]LEVEL9/[3]LEVEL10/[4]LEVEL11/[5]LEVEL12/

Visible segments ≤ 7 (Miller, 1956 — emergent property).

Number_map generated per screen render:
    {1: uuid_at_depth_n-4, 2: uuid_at_depth_n-5, ...}

Jump command: j<num>
- Lookup: O(1)
- Path reconstruction: O(d) where d ≤ visible depth (≤ 10)
- Stack assignment: O(d)
- Jump history maintained for return navigation (jb)

Navigation time is constant with respect to total item count.
Formal proof in /docs/(O)1_COMPUTATIONAL_ANALYSIS.md

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6. ACTIVITY VIEW (TEMPORAL AGGREGATION)
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Activity view shows all changes across all notebooks:
- Global mode: all root notebooks
- Notebook mode: specific notebook and its descendants

Implementation:

    git log --all --grep <uuid_pattern> --pretty=format:"%H|%ai|%s|%b"

Results are aggregated, sorted chronologically, paginated.

Each entry displays:
- Action (created, updated, deleted, renamed, restored)
- Type (note, file, sub)
- Title (with smart truncation)
- Location (smart path: .../parent/child)

Deleted items show original location via parent UUID extraction.
Restored items show current location.

Activity is history made visible — not a log, but a narrative.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
7. UNIFIED SEARCH WITH TYPE/ACTION FILTERS
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Single search interface finds all items regardless of state.
Query syntax supports any order of filters:

    s <action>* <type>* <text>

Action filters:
    deleted*      → items with DELETED in commit history
    created*      → items with CREATED in commit history
    edited*       → items with UPDATED/EDITED in commit history
    renamed*      → items with RENAMED in commit history
    restored*     → items with RESTORED in commit history

Type filters:
    note*         → notes only (not files)
    file*         → files only (by extension)
    sub*          → subnotebooks only

Text query:
    Any remaining words become substring search across titles/content.

Results are merged from three sources:
    Current items (live search)
    Deleted items (reconstructed from commits before deletion)
    Renamed items (UUID-tracked across name changes)

Deduplication by UUID ensures each item appears once.
Sorting by date (newest first) with 50-item limit.

Search does not distinguish between current, deleted, or renamed.
All writing is equally findable.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
8. COMPLETE HIERARCHY RESURRECTION
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Deletion commits to Git; data is not removed.
Search finds UUID of deleted item via deleted* filter.
Commit before deletion is located via:

    git log --before <deletion_commit> --grep uuid:<UUID>

Full hierarchy is extracted from that commit.
Three-file structure is reconstructed in temporary directory.

Restoration process:
- Notes content merged into live notes.json (UUID-keyed)
- File content merged into live files.json (UUID-keyed)
- Structure updated to include item in parent's hierarchy

Subnotebooks restored with all nested content via recursive UUID collection:

    def _collect_all_uuids(notebook_data):
        # Recursively collects UUIDs of notebook, all notes, all subnotebooks
        # Enables filtered content merge

One key press restores item to current structure (original location by default).
UUID unchanged. Temporal continuity preserved.
Git commit: "RESTORED <type>: <title> | to <location>"

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
9. PERMANENT ERASURE WITH GIT-FILTER-REPO INTEGRATION
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Soft delete: removes from current view, remains in history.
Hard delete: removes from Git history entirely.

Hard delete implementation:

    import git_filter_repo  # Dynamic loading via importlib
    git_filter_repo.main()  # Programmatic execution

Process:
- Locate item in current structure
- Identify all commits containing its UUID
- Run git-filter-repo on relevant files (structure.json, notes.json, files.json)
- Remove from current view
- Git garbage collection (aggressive --prune=now)

This is the only operation that breaks UUID continuity.
It is presented as "erase" with explicit confirmation.
GDPR compliance emerges from this capability.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
10. TIMELINE STATE RECONSTRUCTION
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Any item at any commit can be reconstructed via t command:

    git log --grep uuid:<UUID> --all --pretty=format:"%H|%ai|%s"

Each commit represents a version where the item changed.
Results sorted chronologically (newest first).

For any selected version:

    git show <commit_hash>:structure.json
    git show <commit_hash>:notes.json
    git show <commit_hash>:files.json

Recursive extraction preserves complete hierarchy.
Temporary directories isolate reconstructed state.
Display mode indicates historical context (read-only).

Timeline shows evolution. Search shows existence.
Both use the same Git temporal database. Both are separate interfaces.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
11. CRASH RECOVERY WITH UUID KEYING
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

External editor sessions spawn background autosave thread.
Every 30 seconds, temporary file content is saved to:

    .recovery/{note_title}_{uuid[-6:]}.{ext}

On notebook access, recovery system checks for orphaned files.
If found and newer than last saved state, content is restored.

Restoration process:
- Compare recovery timestamp with note.updated
- If newer, update note content
- Commit to Git with note edit message
- Remove recovery file

UUID keying ensures recovery files map to correct notes even after:
- Renames
- Moves between notebooks
- Application crashes
- System restarts

