                    HUMAN COGNITION AS PRIOR ART
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The patterns this system implements are not inventions.
They are observations of how human cognition already works.

SPATIAL MEMORY
    Humans navigate by relative position, not absolute path.
    "Third drawer on the left" precedes "/home/user/drawer/third".
    Numbered items [1][2][3] match innate spatial indexing.
    This system implements what brains already do.

TEMPORAL MEMORY
    Humans recall by "before" and "after", not timestamps.
    "Before I deleted it" is natural language.
    Unified search across all states matches episodic recall.
    Activity view matches "what changed recently".
    This system implements what brains already do.

WORKING MEMORY
    Humans hold 4-7 items consciously (Miller, 1956).
    Fish-eye display shows exactly 4-7 visible segments.
    Page indicators maintain orientation without overload.
    This system respects innate cognitive limits.

RECOGNITION OVER RECALL
    Humans recognize faster than they recall.
    Numbered items are recognized; paths must be recalled.
    Commands ([C]reate, [V]iew) use recognition, not memorization.
    This system implements what brains already do.

AFFORDANCE PERCEPTION
    Humans perceive action possibilities directly (Gibson, 1979).
    Numbered items afford "press number".
    Footer options afford "press letter".
    No training required. The interface teaches itself.
    This system implements what brains already do.

COGNITIVE DISAPPEARANCE
    When tool and thought align, the tool disappears.
    Expert drivers don't think about steering.
    Expert writers don't think about keyboards.
    This system disappears. Only the writing remains.
    This is not a feature. It is the absence of friction.

EMBODIED COGNITION
    Commands migrate to muscle memory (Barsalou, 1999).
    j3 becomes reflex, not conscious decision.
    The body remembers what the mind forgets.
    This system implements embodied interaction.

FLOW STATE
    Uninterrupted writing enables flow (Csikszentmihlyi, 1990).
    No notifications. No interruptions. No modals.
    The system waits. The user writes.
    This system enables what brains already do.

